fr:mainmatter.html:p:
Even when we don't write the set braces, though, the premises of the argument still make up a set, not a list. So the argument p \land q, 
eg r \;/\; 
eg p \lor r is the very same argument as the argument 
eg r, p \land q \;/\; 
eg p \lor r: it has the same set of premises and the same conclusion.

However, the conclusion of an argument is separate---which sentence is the conclusion really does matter. The argument p \land q, 
eg r \;/\; 
eg p \lor r is a completely different argument from p \land q, 
eg p \lor r \;/\; 
eg r: these two arguments have different sets of premises as well as different conclusions.

         Remember, any set of arguments is a logic, so there's a ton of freedom here.
        You already know about the empty and universal logics.
        Here are some more examples.

the logic that contains only the two arguments p \;/\; p and p \land  q \;/\; p;

the logic that contains all and only the arguments with the conclusion p;

the logic that contains an argument \Gamma  \;/\; A if and only if A is a member of \Gamma ;

the logic that contains all and only the arguments with a finite set of premises;

the logic that contains all and only the arguments with an infinite set of premises.

The key new ideas in this lecture are the idea of a matrix, and of the logic determined by a matrix.
We've seen four examples of this idea, and used them to name four particular logics:

designating \mathsf {\mathbf {T}} in the Boolean structure gives us a matrix that determines classical logic;

designating \mathsf {\mathbf {T}} in the strong Kleene structure gives us a matrix that determines the logic K3;

designating \mathsf {\mathbf {T}} and \mathsf {\mathbf {*}} in the strong Kleene structure gives us a matrix that determines the logic LP; and

designating \mathsf {\mathbf {T}} and \mathsf {\mathbf {B}} in the Dunn-Belnap structure gives us a matrix that determines the logic FDE.
